SIMPLE: placard
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Placard
<hw>Pla*card"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr.
<ets>plaquer</ets> to lay or clap on, <ets>plaque</ets> plate, tablet;
probably from Dutch, cf. D. <ets>plakken</ets> to paste, post up,
<ets>plak</ets> a flat piece of wood.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A public
proclamation; a manifesto or edict issued by authority.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All <qex>placards</qex> or edicts are published in his name.</q>
<rj><qau>Howell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Permission given by authority; a license; <as>as, to
give a <ex>placard</ex> to do something</as>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>ller.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A written or printed paper, as an advertisement or a
declaration, posted, or to be posted, in a public place; a
poster.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Anc. Armor)</fld> <def>An extra plate on the lower
part of the breastplate or backplate.</def>
<rj><au>Planch⟦eacute⟧.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <ety>[Cf. <er>Placket</er>.]</ety> <def>A kind of
stomacher, often adorned with jewels, worn in the fifteenth century and
later.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Placard</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Placard
<hw>Pla*card"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Placarded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Placarding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To post placards
upon or within; <as>as, to <ex>placard</ex> a wall, to <ex>placard</ex>
the city</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To announce by placards; <as>as, to <ex>placard</ex>
a sale</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Placate</ent>⟦br⟧
